definition: This term is not new, I believe. In my view, these cells have a pattern of axonal branching similar to typical basket cells, and also display the curved pre-terminal axons typical of basket cells. At difference with the other types of basket cells (common and large basket cells), their axonal plexus form abundant ascending and descending branches that span several layers. Usually these axons distribute within the space of a column as defined in the proposed manuscript.

definition: A cell in LIV of primary sensory cortex with local dendritic arbor with axonal arbor typical of an excitatory glutamatergic cell that arborizes mainly in within the home layer and upper layers.

See Staiger et al 2004, cerebral cortex, 14(6):690-701. The cell is an intermediate between a spiny stellate and a pyramidal cell in terms of the dendritic arbor. The axonal arborization and branching pattern is typical from an excitatory cell.

A typical supragranular excitatory cell. Pyramidal-shaped dendritic arbor and axonal arborization and branching pattern is typical from an excitatory cell that innervated the home layer and deeper ones.

Local pericellular arbor cells (lpbc). These tiny cells were recognized by their dense, 'curvy'<c2>?, complex, and very compact axonal arbor on both radial and tangential dimensions. However, as an exception, some of these cells had a few relatively long descending/ascending axonal branches with numerous boutons (Lund and Lewis, 1993; Zaitsev et al. 2009). Similar cells were described in cat visual cortex as clutch cells (Kisvarday et al. 1985)

This group may contain several kinds of neurons. The cells are generally with a vertically oriented dendritic field. The axon rises from the pial side of the cell and continues as either a single process, or 2-3 rising collaterals which give rise in turn to short lateral terminal branches (Lund and Lewis, 1993)

Neurons with soma in layers III-IV; multipolar or bitufted dendrites; axonal tree sends fibers in a vertical orientation both towards upper and lower layers and less or no fibers in the horizontal orientation and remains in the width of the cortical column. This interneuron inhibits layers below and above it's own layer.

Neurons with soma in layers III-V; multipolar or bitufted dendrites; axonal fibers ascend towards pial surface while giving rich branches on the way. The axonal tree tends to remain withing the cortical width. This type of interneuron inhibits predominalty cells from upper layers within the same cortical column.

Definition  Neurons with soma in layers III-V; multipolar or bitufted dendrites; while descending towards the white matter the axonal branches remain predominately in the same column  and give small collaterals on the way. Occasionally small axonal branches are found around the soma.  This type of interneuron inhibits predominantly cells deep layer and occasionally nearby cells withing the same cortical column.
Densely packed arborization within the layer of the parent soma with additional loose arborizarions that extend away from the layer of the parent soma in any direction
